âœ… What is a Trigger?

A Trigger is a set of instructions that automatically runs (i.e., gets triggered) when a certain event occurs on a table or view.

    ğŸ—£ï¸ In simple words: "If someone inserts/updates/deletes a row, automatically do thisâ€¦"

ğŸ§© Triggers Have Two Main Parts:

    Trigger Function â†’ This is the actual logic/code to run

    Trigger â†’ This connects the function to a specific table + event

ğŸ”¥ When Do Triggers Fire?

You can create triggers on these actions:
Action	Meaning
INSERT	When a new row is added
UPDATE	When a row is updated
DELETE	When a row is removed
TRUNCATE	When a table is emptied

You can fire them:

    BEFORE the action (to validate/change data)

    AFTER the action (to log or sync something)

    INSTEAD OF (used with views)

ğŸ§ª Example Use Case: Logging Insertions

Letâ€™s say you have a students table, and you want to log every insert into a separate log_table.
ğŸ§± Step 1: Create Main Table

CREATE TABLE students (
  id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,
  name TEXT,
  age INT
);

ğŸ“˜ Step 2: Create Log Table

CREATE TABLE student_logs (
  student_id INT,
  name TEXT,
  logged_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT now()
);

ğŸ§  Step 3: Create Trigger Function

CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION log_student_insert()
RETURNS TRIGGER AS $$
BEGIN
  INSERT INTO student_logs(student_id, name)
  VALUES (NEW.id, NEW.name);

  RETURN NEW;
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;

    ğŸ”‘ NEW = refers to the new row being inserted

ğŸš€ Step 4: Create the Trigger

CREATE TRIGGER after_student_insert
AFTER INSERT ON students
FOR EACH ROW
EXECUTE FUNCTION log_student_insert();

Now, whenever you insert a student:

INSERT INTO students(name, age) VALUES ('Mittu', 21);

A new row gets added to student_logs automatically ğŸ’¥
ğŸ’¡ Trigger Keywords
Keyword	Meaning
NEW	Refers to new data (for INSERT/UPDATE)
OLD	Refers to old data (for UPDATE/DELETE)
FOR EACH ROW	Runs the trigger for each row
FOR EACH STATEMENT	Runs once per query, not per row
ğŸ§¯ BEFORE vs AFTER

    BEFORE â†’ You can change or cancel the operation

    AFTER â†’ You can log, notify, or cascade changes

ğŸ›¡ï¸ INSTEAD OF Trigger (For Views)

Since you can't directly insert into a view, you can use INSTEAD OF to handle what should happen.
ğŸ“¦ Example: BEFORE UPDATE to Set Timestamp

Letâ€™s say we want to automatically update a modified_at timestamp on row updates:
Add Column:

ALTER TABLE students ADD COLUMN modified_at TIMESTAMP;

Trigger Function:

CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION set_modified_time()
RETURNS TRIGGER AS $$
BEGIN
  NEW.modified_at = now();
  RETURN NEW;
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;

Trigger:

CREATE TRIGGER before_student_update
BEFORE UPDATE ON students
FOR EACH ROW
EXECUTE FUNCTION set_modified_time();

âš ï¸ Best Practices

âœ… Keep trigger functions small and simple
âœ… Avoid long logic or external API calls inside triggers
âœ… Use for auditing, validation, timestamps, cascading data
âŒ Donâ€™t overuse â€” hard to debug sometimes
ğŸ§  Summary
Component	Example
Trigger Event	AFTER INSERT
Trigger Function	Logic that logs or modifies
NEW / OLD	Refers to row values
Trigger Timing	BEFORE, AFTER, INSTEAD OF
